Male and female diagnostic characters . ( Figs. 3 , 4 A;
Table 1
). Maxillary palpus with apical pale scales on all 5 palpomeres; palpomere 1 with apical white scales; pedicel with dorsal and ventrolateral patches of small white spatulate scales; mid-portion of proboscis with large area of variable pale scaling on dorsum, laterally, and/or on venter; postspiracular area with small ventral patch of white scales (may be present or absent on males); wing normally with 7 pale fringe spots; M 1 + 2 fork with white scales (may be 1–3 scales or obscure on males); hindtarsomeres 1 and 2 without apical pale scales on dorsum; terga I, III–VIII normally with white scales; female cerci with erect white scales; male gonocoxite with erect white scales to apex; accessory setae on gonocoxite of unequal length; internal seta of gonocoxite with long gradually attenuated tip.

